Plotting tools in nilearn
=========================

Nilearn comes with a set of plotting functions for easy visualization of
Nifti-like images such as statistical maps mapped onto anatomical images
or onto glass brain representation, anatomical images, functional/EPI images,
region specific mask images.

See :ref:`plotting` for more details.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 15-17

We will first retrieve data from nilearn provided (general-purpose)
datasets.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 17-39

.. code-block:: Python


    from nilearn import datasets

    # haxby dataset to have EPI images and masks
    haxby_dataset = datasets.fetch_haxby()

    # print basic information on the dataset
    print(
        f"First subject anatomical nifti image (3D) is at: {haxby_dataset.anat[0]}"
    )
    print(
        f"First subject functional nifti image (4D) is at: {haxby_dataset.func[0]}"
    )

    haxby_anat_filename = haxby_dataset.anat[0]
    haxby_mask_filename = haxby_dataset.mask_vt[0]
    haxby_func_filename = haxby_dataset.func[0]

    # one motor activation map
    stat_img = datasets.load_sample_motor_activation_image()






.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none

    [fetch_haxby] Dataset found in /home/runner/nilearn_data/haxby2001
    First subject anatomical nifti image (3D) is at: /home/runner/nilearn_data/haxby2001/subj2/anat.nii.gz
    First subject functional nifti image (4D) is at: /home/runner/nilearn_data/haxby2001/subj2/bold.nii.gz




.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 40-45

Nilearn plotting functions
--------------------------

Plotting statistical maps: `plot_stat_map`
``````````````````````````````````````````

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 45-48

.. code-block:: Python


    from nilearn import plotting








.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 49-51

Visualizing t-map image on EPI template with manual
positioning of coordinates using cut_coords given as a list

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 51-55

.. code-block:: Python

    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img, threshold=3, title="plot_stat_map", cut_coords=[36, -27, 66]
    )




.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_001.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_001.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4affb3c2e0>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 56-58

It's also possible to visualize volumes in a LR-flipped "radiological" view
Just set radiological=True

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 58-67

.. code-block:: Python

    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        threshold=3,
        title="plot_stat_map",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 66],
        radiological=True,
    )





.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_002.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_002.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4aa110e290>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 68-74

Making interactive visualizations: `view_img`
`````````````````````````````````````````````
An alternative to :func:`~nilearn.plotting.plot_stat_map` is to use
:func:`~nilearn.plotting.view_img` that gives more interactive
visualizations in a web browser. See :ref:`interactive-stat-map-plotting`
for more details.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 74-81

.. code-block:: Python

    from nilearn.plotting import view_img

    view = view_img(stat_img, threshold=3)
    # In a Jupyter notebook, if ``view`` is the output of a cell, it will
    # be displayed below the cell
    view

          // On load: build all figures

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 82-84

uncomment this to open the plot in a web browser:
view.open_in_browser()

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 86-88

It's also possible to visualize volumes in a LR-flipped "radiological" view
Just set radiological=True

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 88-93

.. code-block:: Python

    view_radio = view_img(
        stat_img, threshold=3, title="radiological view", radiological=True
    )
    view_radio

e.hide&lt;&quot;u&quot;?e.hide:!1,e.img=document.getElementById(e.img),e.canvas=document.createElement(&quot;canvas&quot;),e.context=e.canvas.getContext(&quot;2d&quot;),e.canvas.width=e.img.width,e.canvas.height=e.img.height,e.context.drawImage(e.img,0,0,e.img.width,e.img.height,0,0,e.img.width,e.img.height),e}function brainsprite(e){let t=initBrain(e);t=initCanvas(t,e.canvas),t=initSprite(t,e.sprite,e.nbSlice),e.overlay&amp;&amp;(t=initOverlay(t,e.overlay.sprite,e.overlay.nbSlice)),e.colorMap&amp;&amp;(t.colorMap=initColorMap(e.colorMap));const n=function(l,a){if(!a)return NaN;let i=NaN,o=1/0;const c=a.canvas.width,d=a.context.getImageData(0,0,c,1).data;for(let s=0;s&lt;c;s++){const r=Math.abs(d[s*4]-l[0])+Math.abs(d[s*4+1]-l[1])+Math.abs(d[s*4+2]-l[2]);r&lt;o&amp;&amp;(i=s,o=r)}return i*(a.max-a.min)/(c-1)+a.min},Y=function(){const l={};if(t.overlay&amp;&amp;!t.nanValue)try{l.XW=Math.round(t.numSlice.X%t.nbCol),l.XH=Math.round((t.numSlice.X-l.XW)/t.nbCol),t.contextRead.clearRect(0,0,1,1),t.contextRead.drawImage(t.overlay.sprite,l.XW*t.nbSlice.Y+t.numSlice.Y,l.XH*t.nbSlice.Z+t.nbSlice.Z-t.numSlice.Z-1,1,1,0,0,1,1);const t.voxelValue=NaN},M=function(l,a,i){for(let o=0;o&lt;3;++o)l[o]=i[0]*a[o][0]+i[1]*a[o][1]+i[2]*a[o][2]+i[3]*a[o][3]},C=[0,0,0],Z=function(){M(C,t.affine,[t.numSlice.X+1,t.numSlice.Y+1,t.numSlice.Z+1,1]),t.coordinatesSlice.X=C[0],t.coordinatesSlice.Y=C[1],t.coordinatesSlice.Z=C[2]};return uncomment this to open the plot in a web browser:

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 98-103

Plotting statistical maps in a glass brain: `plot_glass_brain`
``````````````````````````````````````````````````````````````

Now, the t-map image is mapped on glass brain representation where glass
brain is always a fixed background template

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 103-105

.. code-block:: Python

    plotting.plot_glass_brain(stat_img, title="plot_glass_brain", threshold=3)

Plotting ROIs (here the mask): `plot_roi`
`````````````````````````````````````````

Visualizing ventral temporal region image from haxby dataset overlaid on
subject specific anatomical image
with coordinates positioned automatically on region of interest (roi)

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 119-123

.. code-block:: Python

    plotting.plot_roi(
        haxby_mask_filename, bg_img=haxby_anat_filename, title="plot_roi"
    )

Plotting :term:`EPI` image: `plot_epi`
``````````````````````````````````````

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 126-137

.. code-block:: Python


    # Import image processing tool
    from nilearn import image

    # Compute the voxel_wise mean of functional images across time.
    # Basically reducing the functional image from 4D to 3D
    mean_haxby_img = image.mean_img(haxby_func_filename)

    # Visualizing mean image (3D)
    plotting.plot_epi(mean_haxby_img, title="plot_epi")

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 138-140

A call to plotting.show is needed to display the plots when running
in script mode (ie outside IPython)

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 140-142

.. code-block:: Python

    plotting.show()








.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 143-151

Thresholding plots
------------------

Using ``threshold`` value alongside with ``vmin`` and ``vmax`` parameters
enable us to mask certain values in the image.

Plotting without threshold
``````````````````````````

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 151-159

.. code-block:: Python


    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        display_mode="ortho",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 60],
        title="No plotting threshold",
    )




.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_007.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_007.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4adb149300>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 160-165

Plotting threshold set to 1
```````````````````````````

When plotting threshold is set to 1, the values between -1 and 1
are masked in the plot.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 165-174

.. code-block:: Python


    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        threshold=1,
        display_mode="ortho",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 60],
        title="plotting threshold=1",
    )




.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_008.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_008.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4afe63aec0>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 175-179

Plotting threshold set to 1 with ``vmin=0``
```````````````````````````````````````````

Setting ``vmin=0``, it is possible to plot only positive image values.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 179-190

.. code-block:: Python


    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        threshold=1,
        cmap="inferno",
        display_mode="ortho",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 60],
        title="plotting threshold=1, vmin=0",
        vmin=0,
    )




.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_009.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_009.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4afe013460>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 191-195

Plotting threshold set to 1 with ``vmax=0``
```````````````````````````````````````````

Setting ``vmax=0``, it is possible to plot only negative image values.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 195-206

.. code-block:: Python


    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        threshold=1,
        cmap="inferno",
        display_mode="ortho",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 60],
        title="plotting threshold=1, vmax=0",
        vmax=0,
    )




.. image-sg:: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_010.png
   :alt: plot demo plotting
   :srcset: /auto_examples/01_plotting/images/sphx_glr_plot_demo_plotting_010.png
   :class: sphx-glr-single-img


.. rst-class:: sphx-glr-script-out

 .. code-block:: none


    <nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.OrthoSlicer object at 0x7f4ad788c400>



.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 207-212

Visualizing without a colorbar on the right side
------------------------------------------------

The argument ``colorbar`` should be set to ``False`` to show plots without
a colorbar on the right side.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 212-221

.. code-block:: Python


    plotting.plot_stat_map(
        stat_img,
        display_mode="ortho",
        cut_coords=[36, -27, 60],
        colorbar=False,
        title="no colorbar",
    )

   :alt: plot demo plotting

   :class: sphx-glr-single-img
